{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 11:47:22.294396", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — MPLS lab\\nDate: (current state captured during analysis)\\n\\n1) Executive summary\\n- Symptom: host_1 (10.1.1.2) cannot reach host_2 (10.7.2.2) or host_3 (10.7.3.2). Host_2 and host_3 can reach each other normally.\\n- Primary anomaly: MPLS forwarding along the path from switch_1 toward the egress domain is failing — packets are being dropped on an intermediate switch because the MPLS label does not have a matching forwarding entry.\\n- Localization: The most concrete failure point observed is switch_4 (packets are explicitly dropped there when an MPLS label lookup misses). There is also evidence of inconsistent label mappings across other switches (some switches have entries for particular labels, others do not).\\n- Root cause (most likely): Incomplete / inconsistent MPLS label forwarding table population (MyIngress.mpls_tbl) on one or more intermediate switches (confirmed missing mapping on switch_4 for label 1). As a result LSP/label distribution is not consistent end-to-end and MPLS packets are dropped.\\n\\n2) Symptom and measurement summary\\n- High-level reachability (get_reachability):\\n  - host_2 ↔ host_3: OK (0% loss, RTTs ~2–3 ms).\\n  - host_1 → host_2 and host_1 → host_3: status \"unknown\" in aggregated summary.\\n- Active ping tests:\\n  - pings initiated from host_1 to host_2 and host_3 timed out (commands exceeded timeout).\\n  - pings initiated from host_2 and host_3 to host_1 also timed out.\\n- Host interface/state snapshots:\\n  - host_1: eth0 up, addr 10.1.1.2/24. ip route shows 10.1.1.0/24 dev eth0 and also entries showing 10.7.2.0/24 and 10.7.3.0/24 via eth0 (odd but not necessarily the immediate cause of the drop).\\n  - host_2: eth0 up, addr 10.7.2.2/24.\\n  - host_3: eth0 up, addr 10.7.3.2/24.\\n- Observed behavior: host_1 transmits (TX packets shown on its eth0) but receives nothing back; intermediate switches are processing MPLS packets and some are dropping them.\\n\\n3) Evidence from switch logs and control plane inspection\\n- switch_1 (ingress from host_1) shows MPLS processing and an mpls_tbl hit for label 3:\\n  - Log excerpt: \"Applying table \\'MyIngress.mpls_tbl\\' ... Table \\'MyIngress.mpls_tbl\\': hit with handle 2 ... Action entry: MyIngress.mpls_forward - 30100,3, ... Transmitting packet of size 102 out of port 3\"\\n  - Interpretation: switch_1 is forwarding an MPLS-labeled packet (label 3) onto the network.\\n- switch_4 shows explicit packet drops due to missing MPLS entry:\\n  - Log excerpt: \"Applying table \\'MyIngress.mpls_tbl\\' ... Looking up key: * hdr.mpls.label : 000001 ... Table \\'MyIngress.mpls_tbl\\': miss ... Action entry is MyIngress.drop ... mark_to_drop(standard_metadata) ... Dropping packet at the end of ingress\"\\n  - Interpretation: switch_4 received an MPLS packet with label = 1 but has no mpls_tbl entry for that label and so is dropping the packet.\\n- switch_7 shows correct egress-border behavior for some packets (stripping MPLS, converting to IPv4):\\n  - Log excerpt: \"Action entry: MyIngress.mpls_forward - a070302,4, ... Applying table \\'MyEgress.check_is_egress_border\\' ... Table \\'MyEgress.check_is_egress_border\\': hit ... Action MyEgress.is_egress_border ... hdr.mpls.setInvalid() ... Transmitting packet ... Deparsing header \\'ipv4\\' ... Transmitting packet of size 98 out of port 4\"\\n  - Interpretation: switch_7 has entries to decapsulate MPLS and forward as IPv4 to attached hosts (host_2/host_3 domain) — that side looks configured.\\n\\n4) Localization of fault(s)\\n- Primary failure node: switch_4\\n  - Concrete evidence: switch_4 log shows a miss in MyIngress.mpls_tbl for label 1 and immediate drop of those packets.\\n- Secondary observations:\\n  - switch_1 has mpls_tbl entries (label 3) and is forwarding; switch_7 has egress behavior for some labels. This indicates that some switches have label/state configured but at least one key intermediate (switch_4) lacks the mapping for a label used by ingress, creating an LSP break.\\n  - The mismatch of label values (e.g., switch_1 forwarding label 3, switch_4 missing label 1) suggests inconsistent label assignment or incomplete label programming across the MPLS domain.\\n\\n5) Root-cause assessment\\n- Most likely root cause: inconsistent/incomplete MPLS label forwarding table population across the data plane (MyIngress.mpls_tbl). Specifically, switch_4 is missing a mapping for an MPLS label (label 1) used by upstream forwarding, leading to packet drops there. This breaks the LSP from host_1 toward the egress (host_2/host_3).\\n- Contributing/related observations:\\n  - The logs show different labels and different table outcomes on different switches (some hits, some misses), which is consistent with either (a) label distribution/configuration not applied uniformly, or (b) control-plane logic assigning different label values or failing to program forwarding entries on some switches.\\n  - Host routing displays unusual link-local route entries for remote subnets on the hosts (host_1 shows 10.7.2.0/24 and 10.7.3.0/24 as link routes). That is suspicious/configuration-noise but the immediate deterministic drop is in the MPLS forwarding plane on the switches, not simple host-route misconfiguration.\\n\\n6) Limitations / tool notes\\n- Attempts to dump certain table entries via bmv2 table-dump returned syntax-like errors from the tool wrapper (the direct table-dump calls returned a python/format error), but bmv2 logs provided sufficient evidence of hits/misses and dropped packets.\\n- The mapping of P4 logical port numbers to topology port names (eth0/eth1 etc.) was not present in the logs, so port-number ↔ topology-edge mapping is inferred from behavior rather than an explicit mapping table. The drop is identified by switch_4 logs independent of exact port-to-interface numbering.\\n\\n7) Summary / concise findings\\n- Observed failure: host_1 cannot reach hosts in the 10.7.x network; host_2 and host_3 can reach each other.\\n- Where packets fail: switch_4 (explicit mpls_tbl miss → drop).\\n- Likely root cause: missing/inconsistent MPLS forwarding entries (label mapping) on intermediate switches (switch_4 confirmed missing label 1). This causes the LSP from switch_1 toward the egress (switch_7 / host_2/host_3) to break.\\n- Additional oddities: inconsistent label values across switches (some switches show label 3, some expect label 1), and unusual host route entries observed on hosts (possible configuration artifacts).\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- enumerate exact mpls_tbl entries on each switch (attempt another table dump or different method) to show which labels are present/absent per switch, and\\n- map P4 port numbers to topology interfaces to give a precise forwarding path and confirm the LSP break location unambiguously.\\n\\n(Report stops here — no remediation steps provided per your instruction.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='33b973aa-02d4-4f1e-8817-feb3e3b6174f'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
